{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01GcbBCndeQCS2Ad7GGqY4h8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WbYJDTt4h7PgkSwv3j2tAT","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Files placed in subdirectories of the watched root are detected and processed, not only files in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure mode is 'daemon doesn't watch subdirectories' — caused by misconfiguring the watcher (e.g., forgot recursive: true). Mocking the watcher to return subdirectory events hides this real failure. You need actual OS filesystem watching behavior to catch whether the daemon correctly enables recursive watching.","test_description":"Create a watched root directory with subdirectories, place a test file inside a subdirectory, verify the real watcher emits an event for the nested file, then verify the daemon's processing queue includes it and the transformation is applied (output generated).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Deduplication logic correctly ignores a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The dedup logic is in-process state tracking (Set of seen paths with timestamp windows). While the core logic is deterministic, you need to simulate realistic watcher event streams — multiple events arriving in quick succession — to test whether the daemon's dedup correctly handles them. Mocking at Unit level (just testing timestamp comparison) misses event-sequencing failures.","test_description":"Simulate two rapid filesystem events for the same file path by triggering the watcher callback twice in quick succession (or using a mock watcher that emits duplicate events), verify the daemon adds the file to the processing queue only once within the dedup window, and verify processing would occur again if a duplicate event arrives after the window expires.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This specifically tests the daemon's handling of OS-level event multiplicity — an actual OS behavior where a single file write triggers multiple watcher events (e.g., 'add' then 'change', or 'change' twice). Mocking the watcher to always emit one event per file completely hides this real failure. Real OS file I/O and real watcher event delivery are required.","test_description":"Write to a real file in the watched directory in a way that causes the OS filesystem watcher to emit multiple events (e.g., create + modify), verify that despite multiple watcher callbacks firing, the daemon's processing queue contains the file only once, and verify the output is generated exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure mode depends on real filesystem operations (directory deletion/recreation) and the real watcher library's error handling. When the directory is deleted, the real watcher may throw errors, stop delivering events, or enter an error state. Mocking a 'directory deleted' event doesn't test whether the daemon detects the actual condition, handles recovery, and successfully watches the recreated directory. Real OS filesystem operations are required.","test_description":"Start the daemon watching a real directory, delete the directory using real filesystem operations, verify the watcher detects the deletion (may error or stop delivering events), recreate the directory and place a test file in it, verify the daemon automatically resumes watching without restart, and verify the new file is processed normally.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive simultaneously or in quick succession, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps, not the order of arrival events.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Testing timestamp-ordered processing requires real files with actual creation timestamps (or controlled mtimes) to verify the daemon reads timestamps correctly. However, real OS event ordering is not required — you can use a mock watcher that emits events in a different order than creation time to force the sorting logic to work. Integration level (real files + mock watcher) is sufficient; System level is not needed.","test_description":"Create multiple files in a watched directory with controlled creation timestamps (created in sequence or with mtime adjusted), configure a mock watcher to emit events in a different order than creation time, verify the daemon processes them according to creation timestamp order by checking output timestamps or processing log order.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This tests the daemon's handling of file locks and write-in-progress conditions. OS file locking behavior is platform-specific (flock on Unix, different mechanisms on Windows) and can't be reliably mocked. If you mock the file read to always succeed, you miss the real failure: 'daemon tries to process a locked or incomplete file and fails.' You need another real process writing to the file and real OS file-open behavior to trigger the actual error condition.","test_description":"Start the daemon watching a directory, create a file and begin writing to it from another process without closing it, trigger a watcher event for the file, verify the daemon either detects the write-in-progress condition and retries, or fails gracefully when attempting to open/read the locked file, then complete the write and verify the file is successfully processed.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13549,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13549},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"82987755-d97f-4649-b359-66b17f66e4c9","uuid":"ec72250a-2986-4776-8575-c4dd7fec42ce"}
